body:
The issue is still active. spdlog 1.11.0. SPDLOG_* macros evaluate their arguments regardless of the runtime log level.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <spdlog/spdlog.h>
#include <string_view>

int f(const std::string_view s) {
  std::cout << "hello from f(" << s << ")" << std::endl;
  return 42;
}

int main() {
  spdlog::set_level(spdlog::level::critical);
  SPDLOG_TRACE("log record with side effect: {}", f("trace"));
  SPDLOG_DEBUG("log record with side effect: {}", f("debug"));
  SPDLOG_INFO("log record with side effect: {}", f("info"));
  SPDLOG_WARN("log record with side effect: {}", f("warn"));
  SPDLOG_ERROR("log record with side effect: {}", f("error"));
}
```

Compiled with -DSPDLOG_ACTIVE_LEVEL=SPDLOG_LEVEL_TRACE. The output is:

```bash
$ ./mre
hello from f(trace)
hello from f(debug)
hello from f(info)
hello from f(warn)
hello from f(error)
```

>After much consideration, I decided to remove this feature - It adds 2 additional checks and increases the size and complexity of the generated code.

Does this mean this is not a bug even if, for example, Boost.Log does have these runtime checks and it doesn't evaluate arguments for records with lower levels?
